    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-01-28T15:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-01-28T15:30:00-05:00" n="741"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d741">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.3131/80: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Venezuela</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Villard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caracas</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-01-28T16:00:00-04:30"
                            >January 28, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 8:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9. The Foreign Minister told me today he had been informed that a bill raising
                    the excise tax on imported petroleum to one cent a gallon had been introduced in
                    the United States Congress and probably would be reported favorably February 8.
                    He said that he regarded this development as unfortunate on eve of negotiations
                    for reciprocal trade agreement and that he was telegraphing the Venezuelan
                    Minister in Washington to discuss matter with you as soon as possible.</p>
                <p>While Venezuela is not seriously concerned at prospect of higher excise taxes in
                    the United States for reasons mentioned in my telegram No. 84, December 16,
                        noon,<note n="7" xml:id="d741fn7">Not printed.</note> the Foreign Minister
                    anticipates immediate active interest in the subject on the part of the larger
                    oil companies. Standard Oil representative in Caracas has already inquired as to
                    possibility of a trade agreement with Venezuela.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Villard</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
